        "header": "3Method",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.24231/2606.24231v1/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:FlowR2A structure and training pipeline. We randomly sample action-reward pairs to produce noisy samples𝒛t{\\bm{z}}_{t}. The reward encoder embeds rewardsrrinto a condition embedding. The flow-based action decoder predicts the clean sample based on scene features from the perception encoder and the condition injected via AdaLN, which is supervised by the velocity-matching loss.",
                "position": 377
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.24231/2606.24231v1/x3.png",
                "caption": "Figure 3:FlowR2A inference pipeline. (Left) The action decoder samples each proposal by denoising from a noisy anchor attinitt_{\\mathrm{init}}under CFG with the high-reward conditionrhighr_{\\mathrm{high}}, together producing multiple proposal candidates. (Middle) The mode selector ranks proposals at inference and is supervised by simulated GT labels during stage-2 training. (Right) Sampling space spanned byrhighr_{\\mathrm{high}}andtinitt_{\\mathrm{init}}. See Fig.9for the full version.",
                "position": 467
            }
        ]
